          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818036?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">克里斯·克里斯蒂 (Chris Christie) 6 月 23 日在华盛顿举行的一次会议上发表讲话。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：罗恩·萨克斯/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p><em>前新泽西州州长克里斯·克里斯蒂 (Chris Christie) 7 月 16 日在美国广播公司 (ABC) 的“本周”节目中露面：</em></p><p>乔治·斯蒂芬诺普洛斯：你本周宣布你将进入辩论阶段。你已经有资格进入辩论舞台了。你认为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>会出席吗？</p><p>克里斯蒂先生：乔治，你知道，我知道。我确实认为他会在那里。</p><p> Stephanopolous 先生：真的吗？</p><p>克里斯蒂先生：是的，我想他会在那里。 。 。 。如你所知，我认识他很久了。我认为，他的自负不会允许他有一个他没有参加的大型电视节目。我想如果他坐在贝德明斯特，看着我在缺席的舞台上对他做什么，他会感到非常沮丧。</p><p> Stephanopoulos 先生：听起来你是在引诱他进来。</p><p>克里斯蒂先生：。 。 。我不认为我必须这样做，但我现在很高兴地说，来吧，唐纳德，上台捍卫你的记录。你知道，如果你想成为提名人，你需要捍卫你的记录。在他担任总统四年的时间里，他没有解决共和党人非常关心的很多问题。尽管他拥有共和党国会，但他并没有像他所说的那样废除和取代奥巴马医改。他说他将平衡预算；他增加了 6 万亿美元的国债。他说他要在墨西哥修建隔离墙；他修建了 47 英里长的新墙。你知道，乔治，按照四年内的速度，他需要担任总统 110 年才能完成这堵墙。</p><p>斯蒂芬诺普洛斯先生：目前这些都没有动摇他的支持。 。 。共和党的根基内部。您能说些什么人们还没有听说过的话可以改变他们的想法呢？</p><p>克里斯蒂先生：。 。 。我认为这只是耐心和坚持。作为总统，他的记录并不好。顺便说一句，我们甚至没有谈论三届失败的记录，他在 2018 年输掉了众议院，在 2020 年输掉了参议院和白宫，并在 2022 年带领我们在中期选举中表现糟糕。总统的职位支持率为 35%。不过，乔治，这需要时间。八年来，这个家伙一直是每个共和党初选选民心中的焦点。我参加比赛已经五个星期了。给我一些时间。</p><p>你已经可以看到，当他凌晨一点起床在 Truth Social 上发布关于我的信息时，我想我们就在他的脑海里。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 20:55:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/notable-quotable-trump-christie-and-gop-debates-new-jersey-877ac3a4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/notable-quotable-trump-christie-and-gop-debates-new-jersey-877ac3a4<category>辩论</category><category>共和党</category><category>王牌</category><category>克里斯蒂</category><category>新泽西州</category><category>真相社会</category><category>州长</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>电视/广播</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>社论</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>唐纳德·特朗普</category><category>克里斯·克里斯蒂</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>电视</category><category>收音机</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>社论</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Mexico’s AMLO Makes Xóchitl a Household Name]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>总统对参议员的攻击表明他害怕她以及她传达的信息。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12108107398966324280204590088660892417860"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12108107398966324280204590088660892417860"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/mary-anastasia-ogrady"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BI562_ogrady_AM_20180807122707.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/mary-anastasia-ogrady" itemprop="url" rel="author">玛丽·阿纳斯塔西娅·奥格雷迪</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 16 日下午 4:53 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amlo-makes-xochitl-a-household-name-mexico-presidential-election-coalition-64299752"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817985?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 7 月 4 日，Xochitl Galvez 在墨西哥城向支持者发表讲话。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：亨利·罗梅罗/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Xóchitl Gálvez 是一位墨西哥女性，笑容灿烂，充满乐观的气息。她也是墨西哥总统安德烈斯·曼努埃尔·洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔最可怕的噩梦。</p><p>距离墨西哥 2024 年总统选举还有 10 个月，洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔先生的支持率徘徊在 60% 以上。虽然他无法竞选连任，但他的受欢迎程度很可能会让这位尚未确定姓名的莫雷纳党候选人在 6 月 2 日率先冲过终点线。</p><p>除非出现一个能够团结反对派并刺激高投票率的挑战者。</p><p> 60 岁的墨西哥参议员加尔韦斯女士登场，她宣布打算于 6 月 27 日参选。她获得了全国范围内的广泛关注，这在很大程度上要归功于洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔先生，他显然将她视为威胁。</p><p>总统的担心是正确的。加尔维斯女士是一位聪明的政治家，有着快乐的战士氛围。就在一个月前，莫雷纳似乎是不可能被击败的。这不再是真的。</p><p>莫雷纳带着强劲的宏观经济故事进入了这个选举年。奥夫拉多尔的议程一直是反增长和反制度，但比索的稳定掩盖了许多罪恶。墨西哥货币兑美元汇率低于 17，低于 2021 年的 21。来自美国的强劲汇款流量和独立央行审慎的货币政策是比索走强的主要原因。外国投资在近岸外包的支持下流入制造业也发挥了一定作用。</p><p>奥夫拉多尔搭上了比索稳定的便车，但这归功于他反对的经济自由化：自由贸易、投资者保护和透明的货币政策。尽管如此，墨西哥仍远未发挥其潜力。</p><p>奥夫拉多尔是一位民粹主义者，其政治策略围绕阶级和种族分裂以及不满。国会和法院中阻碍他民族主义议程的反对者被贴上傲慢的势利小人的标签——或者用他的白话来说， <em>“fifis”</em> 。</p><p>墨西哥广泛阵线联盟（由国家行动党、革命制度党和革命民主党组成）已同意支持一名候选人，试图击败莫雷纳。</p><p>加尔维斯女士是报名参加联盟初选的 13 名竞争者之一，该初选将分为两轮，将于 9 月 3 日结束。她距离稳操胜券还很远。其他有力的竞争者包括经验丰富的国家行动党议员圣地亚哥·克里尔和前总统之子、革命制度党党员恩里克·德拉马德里。但奥夫拉多尔将非社会保守派、地位上升的加尔维斯女士作为候选人。</p><p>这位<a href="https://www.pan.senado.gob.mx/integrantes/senadora-bertha-xochitl-galvez-ruiz/" target="_blank" class="icon none">参议员</a>出生在伊达尔戈州，父亲是土著，母亲是混血儿。她的家庭很穷，但她完成了学业，并毕业于墨西哥国立自治大学，获得计算机工程学位。</p><p>她建立了成功的专门从事“智能”建筑的咨询业务。她还成立了一个<a href="https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/tendencias/xochitl-galvez-asi-surgio-la-fundacion-porvenir-que-presidio-la-senadora/" target="_blank" class="icon none">基金会，</a>以对抗土著社区的儿童营养不良问题。在维森特·福克斯总统执政期间（2000-06 年），她担任墨西哥国家土著人民研究所所长。</p><p> 2010 年，她在伊达尔戈州州长竞选中以微弱优势落败——尽管她所在的国家行动党 (PAN) 的资源很少。 2015年，她当选为墨西哥城一个地区的市长。 2018年，她赢得了比例代表制参议院席位。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>了解更多美洲</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/colonial-joe-biden-bullies-a-neighbor-populism-election-guatemala-populism-race-south-america-d4ab1cdb?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">殖民地乔·拜登欺负邻居</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 9 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russias-many-spies-in-mexico-war-global-power-network-putin-south-america-b4b3659f?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">俄罗斯在墨西哥有许多间谍</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 2 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chile-may-have-a-future-after-all-jose-antonio-kast-violence-protest-free-market-south-america-6b06f7ca?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">智利终究还是有未来</a><span class="date">2023 年 6 月 25 日</span></li></ul></div></div><p>在上周的推特<a href="https://twitter.com/XochitlGalvez/status/1678858150546493440" target="_blank" class="icon none">视频</a>中，加尔韦斯女士指出，奥夫拉多夫在国家宫殿举行的每日新闻发布会上连续七天提到了她的名字——一天达 11 次。她用墨西哥湾墨西哥国家石油公司平台起火和格雷罗州<a href="https://elpais.com/mexico/2023-07-11/caos-en-chilpancingo-civiles-se-enfrentan-con-policias-y-toman-el-congreso-de-guerrero-con-un-vehiculo-blindado.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">卡特尔</a>暴力的照片来询问总统除了谈论她是否没有更好的事情可做。</p><p>当奥夫拉多尔意图消灭对手时，法律对他来说并不是任何障碍。在他在每日新闻发布会上指责她反对社会计划后，法院<a href="https://aristeguinoticias.com/1306/mexico/este-es-el-amparo-de-xochitl-galvez-contra-amlo-por-la-mananera/" target="_blank" class="icon none">命令</a>他给予她答复的权利。他拒绝遵守。</p><p>周五，他声称在过去九年中，加尔韦斯女士的公司与政府签订的合同价值超过 8000 万美元。加尔韦斯女士否认了这一指控，称总统的算术错误，他的声明是一个错误。她还表示，他公开了机密税务信息，并威胁对他采取法律行动。</p><p>当他不滥用权力时，他就是公然侮辱她。他称她为精英的傀儡。在上周的新闻发布会上，他试图驳回加尔韦斯女士的候选资格，将她比作一个流动的玉米粉蒸肉小贩，唱着所有墨西哥人在街上都知道的顺口溜。对一个凭借纯粹的决心攀登经济阶梯的女性的居高临下是否是一种制胜策略值得怀疑。</p><p>虽然总统贬低努力工作，但加尔韦斯女士正在向全国谈论其愿望、自由和对制度的尊重。这些是许多墨西哥人可能想更多了解的主题。</p><p><em>写信给 O&#39;Grady@wsj.com</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=F7398B29-80AD-4BFD-BE1E-F1DBF1D77631&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Famlo-makes-xochitl-a-household-name-mexico-presidential-election-coalition-64299752&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">杂志社论报告：虽然蓝色州在个人收入方面遇到了麻烦。图片：美联社综合报道：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">《华尔街日报》互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 20:53:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/amlo-makes-xochitl-a-household-name-mexico-presidential-election-coalition-64299752</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/amlo-makes-xochitl-a-household-name-mexico-presidential-election-coalition-64299752<author><![CDATA[Mary Anastasia O’Grady]]></author><category>墨西哥</category><category>总统选举</category><category>加尔韦斯</category><category>阿姆洛</category><category>委屈</category><category>卡特尔暴力</category><category>经济学</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>加尔韦斯</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>安德烈斯·曼努埃尔·洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Germany in the World’ Review: Reichs, From First to Third]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>年轻的民族国家德国在 20 世纪 30 年代转向法西斯主义和种族灭绝。然而在 1914 年之前，它和法国或英国一样自由。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12108107398966324280204590080563906716420"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818059?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 19世纪末的柏林勃兰登堡门。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿拉米库存照片</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12108107398966324280204590080563906716420"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">约瑟夫·约菲</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 16 日下午 4:52 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/germany-in-the-world-review-reichs-from-first-to-third-da62f1c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>五百年前，我们现在称为德国的土地作为“德意志民族的神圣罗马帝国”而存在。它不是一个真正的帝国，当然也不是神圣的或罗马的，甚至不是特别德国的。它更像是封地、信仰和民族的大杂烩。 1806年，拿破仑结束了这个“帝国”。</p><p>现代德国是经典民族国家中的一个婴儿，诞生于1871年，当时普鲁士将25个小德国联合在一起。统一引发了增长，然后是野心，然后是两次可怕的世界大战。截肢将这个庞然大物缩小到一定大小。今天重新统一的德国是欧洲最大的经济体，也是受人尊敬的世界公民。</p><p>然而，连续性仍然存在，这是大卫·布莱克伯恩（David Blackbourn）的《世界上的德国：全球历史，1500-2000 年》的主题。然而，这些连续性并不像 1941 年的一本著作那样，是从路德到希特勒那样简单的性格即命运的类型。布莱克伯恩先生要求我们用“更广阔的视角”来看待，这表明德国并不是欧洲的异类。</p><p>以德国民族主义为例。他提醒我们，“1860 年代是民族主义史上的关键十年”。这种意识形态由大革命的法国发明，影响了所有新的民族国家：德国、意大利和日本。美国在 1890 年代也经历了一场民族主义狂欢。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/7b3bf44f-b8db-410c-9d26-8805a032d050.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>德皇统治下的德国并不走在<em>特殊道路（Sonderweg）</em>上，这条道路是一条独立的毒路。按照当时的标准来看，1914 年之前的帝国并不比法国或英国更自由。德国奉行法治，并拥有强大的议会和充满活力的新闻界。其政权为何转向种族灭绝？尽管有关大屠杀的文献越来越多，但宇宙之谜仍然悬而未决。</p><p>布莱克伯恩先生建议，“我们应该挑战这样一个根深蒂固的观念，即内陆德国只专注于自己的事务”——自成一体——“而其他国家则改变了欧洲与非欧洲世界之间的关系。”事实上，他认为，“神圣罗马帝国是一个动态的世界。”在接下来的 150 页中，他讲述了德国水手如何操纵航海国家的船只，德国士兵如何在大英帝国和荷兰帝国服役，以及焦躁不安的居民如何从东欧向西半球发起进攻。</p><p>即便如此，德国水手、学者和定居者的全球旅行欲望与真正的全球化者征服和居住在地球四个角落的行为相比，还是无法相提并论。侨民不是帝国，不管有多少德国人在美国定居；无论如何，德国攫取的少数财产在 1919 年凡尔赛和解中都失去了。战败的德国人应该感谢胜利者，让他们免于遭受无数次针对当地人的战争，这些战争在二战后耗尽了殖民列强的鲜血和财富。</p><p>德国（或德语）“帝国”要便宜得多。这是一个文化统治。如果没有歌德和席勒、巴赫和贝多芬、马克思和黑格尔、康德和维特根斯坦、里尔克和曼、弗洛伊德和荣格、爱因斯坦、普朗克和海森堡，我们就无法思考现代性。 GW Pabst 和 Fritz Lang 等德国人书写了电影经典的第一章。卡尔·莱姆勒发明了好莱坞。</p><p>布莱克伯恩先生提醒我们，美国高等教育是按照“德国模式”的形象“重塑”的。哈佛大学、斯坦福大学和约翰·霍普金斯大学（“巴尔的摩的哥廷根”）采用了德国研究型大学的概念。后来，当数千名德国学者在美国避难时，他们获得了一笔悲惨的意外之财——希特勒的“礼物”。</p><p>奇怪的是，这本书的题为“德国文化的胜利”的章节跨越了俾斯麦和希特勒之间的 60 年，但犹太人的重要角色却被忽略了。在此期间，大约有 39 名犹太诺贝尔奖获得者来自德国和奥地利，更多来自<em>中欧</em>其他地区。然后还有像弗兰兹·卡夫卡这样的小说家，还有像阿诺德·勋伯格这样的作曲家，他们打破了这种模式。</p><p>布莱克本先生对不偏不倚的态度值得称赞，有时他也会表现得更好。因此，他将 1942 年最终解决方案制定后的无边屠杀描述为，虽然是“德国主导的”，但却是受德国压迫的人民，特别是东欧人民的“泛欧行动”。这种共谋并没有消除骑手和马之间的区别。纳粹德国设计了该项目并建造了死亡工厂。一些波兰人、乌克兰人等。是愿意合作的人。但他们不是大师。</p><p>在布莱克伯恩先生对两次世界大战的描述中，我们也感受到了类似的“是的，但是”的味道。是的，无限制的潜艇战让美国领先，但德国平民却在封锁下受苦。是的，在第二次战争中，德国的战争是不分青红皂白的残酷，但区域轰炸给德国无辜者带来了可怕的痛苦。</p><p>除了损失和破坏之外，德国是如何如此迅速地从法西斯独裁变成和平的共和国的？美国通过扩大核保护伞解决了德国战后的安全困境。安全孕育美好事物：繁荣、民主和自我遏制。欧洲其他国家不再害怕这个再次成为第一的国家。</p><p>那么“德国问题”已经成为过去了吗？不完全的。正如布莱克伯恩先生指出的那样，十二年前，波兰外交部长表示，他对德国实力的恐惧更甚于对德国无所作为的恐惧。有时教训太深了。被动不再是一项大战略，正如俄罗斯去年入侵乌克兰并迫使德国向受害者借出力量时所明确的那样。</p><p>对于长达近 800 页的《世界上的德国》来说，太多的美好事物也可能适用。这项研究非常精彩，有 80 页的尾注。但中心思想——德国和其他国家一样是一个西方国家——常常被淹没在大量的名称、细节和题外话之中。也就是说，这本书写得非常出色，即使是德国爱好者也会发现丰富的内容。</p><p> <em>Joffe 先生在约翰·霍普金斯大学高级国际研究学院任教。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 20:52:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/germany-in-the-world-review-reichs-from-first-to-third-da62f1c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/germany-in-the-world-review-reichs-from-first-to-third-da62f1c<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>战争罪</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>战争罪</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Summer Is for Salamanders]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>只要有一个池塘、一本书、一只棒球手套和一点想象力——一切皆有可能。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590088350054331516"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590088350054331516"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">克里斯托弗·德·芬克</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 16 日下午 4:51 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/summer-is-for-salamanders-childhood-turtle-book-baseball-tree-fort-ddc3cc98"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817986?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2017 年 3 月 27 日，弗吉尼亚州雪兰多国家公园内一只濒临灭绝的雪兰多蝾螈。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ann 和 Rob Simpson/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> &#39;夏日午后——夏日午后；对我来说，这一直是英语中最美丽的两个词。”亨利·詹姆斯写道。如今，孩子们暑假都做什么呢？</p><p> 20 世纪 50 年代，我以一杯阿华田和一个煮鸡蛋开始了我的生活。然后我会考虑我的选择。我可能会骑着自行车去当地的游泳池，身上裹着一条毛巾，口袋里装着 25 美分的硬币，可以装好幽默卡车。那是一个小型社区游泳池，深度不超过 5 英尺，只有一名救生员，一位女大学生，她让我坐在她的救生员椅子上。当我为她表演水戏时，她鼓掌，尤其是我消失在水下并把腿伸直的那一幕。在灿烂的阳光下，我感觉自己就像一位奥运游泳明星。</p><p>我们的房子后面有一个池塘，沿着小路穿过覆盆子灌木丛。我在水中寻找青蛙和蜥蜴。在炎热的天气里，我会跑到田野里，几乎跳进覆盆子丛中采摘浆果，用舌头抵住上颚将它们压碎，品尝味道和清凉的汁液。然后我坐在池塘边寻找蝾螈。</p><p>一个男孩可以在池塘的倒影中看到自己。一个人很容易忘记曾经有过这样一个池塘。</p><p>我喜欢把手慢慢地滑入水中并舀起蝾螈。我喜欢欣赏它的尾巴、头部和小腿。夏季男孩注意了。</p><p>如果有比在树堡里闲逛、拿着一本《金银岛》和一杯酷爱饮料更好的方式来度过炎热的夏日午后，我很想听听。 “死者的胸口上有十五个人——哟嗬嗬，还有一瓶朗姆酒！”</p><p>我夏天最开心的事情之一就是寻找鳄龟。在我看来，它们是海怪，是恐龙的表亲，有着铁颚，十分凶猛。看到一只鳄龟像潜伏在水面下的潜水艇一样，对我来说是在我自己的私人夏季海洋中的一次冒险。</p><p>一年夏天，我用仿橙色灌木的树枝建造了一座小屋，并用草作为隔热材料。我做了泥饼干，然后在鸡舍的热屋顶上“烘烤”它们。我骑着自行车去加油站玩：杜鹃叶换钱；邮箱是加油泵。溜溜球、Cracker Jack 和 Davy Crockett 帽子；铃声和解码器铃声——我装备精良。</p><p>夜晚，打开窗户，吸入凉爽的空气，蟋蟀和树蛙咯咯地笑，尤吉·贝拉、怀蒂·福特、米基·曼特尔和罗杰·马里斯</p>收音机里传来夏日诸神挥舞着魔法棒的声音。<p></p><p>自从我还是个孩子的时候起，情况就发生了变化。但我仍然认为你可以在炎热的下午给孩子一只棒球手套和一本书，并告诉他有孤独的海龟和蝾螈希望来到池塘边。等一下，仔细听，你可能会听到他说：“哟呵呵呵，还有一瓶朗姆酒！”</p><p> <em>Mr. de Vinck is the author of 17 books, including “Things that Matter Most.”</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B89B2690-0317-40F9-A22B-4C9D280DCCCC&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fsummer-is-for-salamanders-childhood-turtle-book-baseball-tree-fort-ddc3cc98&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Journal Editorial Report: The week&#39;s best and worst from Kim Strassel, Bill McGurn, Mary O&#39;Grady and Dan Henninger. Images: AP/EPA/Shutterstock/Reuters/Zuma Press Composite: Mark Kelly <span class="imageCredit">The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 20:51:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/summer-is-for-salamanders-childhood-turtle-book-baseball-tree-fort-ddc3cc98</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/summer-is-for-salamanders-childhood-turtle-book-baseball-tree-fort-ddc3cc98<category> summer afternoon</category><category> childhood</category><category> salamander</category><category> pond</category><category> book</category><category> baseball glove</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Supreme Court Control Act]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> New ethics proposals from Senate Democrats are a scheme to destroy the Court&#39;s independence. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590082170044941344"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590082170044941344"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">July 16, 2023 4:13 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-supreme-court-control-act-whitehouse-durbin-recusal-ethics-1b2e9bd3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818024?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Senator Sheldon Whitehouse (D-RI) speaking with Senator Dick Durbin (D-IL) at a hearing of the Senate Judiciary Committee on June 13.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Michael Brochstein/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The Supreme Court has finished its business for the summer, but Senate Democrats never finish trashing the Justices. The Judiciary Committee that scoured Brett Kavanaugh&#39;s high-school yearbook is preparing to pass new rules under the guise of ethics reform that are intended to put the Justices on a political leash.</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> The effort is led by Rhode Island Sen. Sheldon Whitehouse and his more senior political front man, Judiciary Chairman Dick Durbin. They&#39;re playing off recent media reports that claim ethics violations without showing any real violations. But that&#39;s enough of an excuse for claiming to want to protect the Court&#39;s reputation while actually destroying it.</p><h4> ***</h4><p> Their Supreme Court Ethics, Recusal, and Transparency Act would require the Court to establish a Code of Conduct within 180 days. It would also set disclosure rules for “gifts, income, and reimbursements required to be disclosed under the Standing Rules of the Senate and the Rules of the House of Representatives.”</p><p> Treating judges like Members of Congress is exactly the wrong model to follow. The nine Justices are appointees with lifetime tenure under the Constitution in order to insulate them from political pressure. Legislators are political actors accountable to voters for their relationships with campaign contributors and interest groups.</p><p> The Senate ethics scheme would drop the Justices into a new political maelstrom. The bill invites ethics complaints alleging that a Justice violates the new rules or “has otherwise engaged in conduct that undermines the integrity of the Supreme Court.” That open-ended standard is an invitation to groups on the left and right to file endless complaints against the Justices to create the appearance of wrongdoing or conflicts of interest.</p><p> The complaints would be handled by a five-member panel of chief judges from the circuit courts. That would further politicize the judiciary by asking lower-court judges to rule on the ethics of Justices who decide whether to hear appeals of their rulings. The judges would be under enormous pressure to act against Justices with a different judicial philosophy.</p><p> The bill also lays out “circumstances requiring disqualification” to hear a case—more commonly known as recusal. The Justices currently make their own decisions on recusal based on relatively narrow criteria such as whether they have a financial interest in a case. Political demands for recusal are becoming more common, but most can be ignored.</p><p> The Senate bill sets up a process for a three-judge panel of judges to review a “motion” by a party for recusal. Such motions would proliferate, as the parties and interests angle to eliminate a Justice they think might rule against them. The Democratic goal here is thinning the Court on a case by case basis to influence decisions. It&#39;s a different means than packing the Court by adding Justices, but the purpose is similar.</p><p> The Founders anticipated this political temptation, which is why they created the judiciary as a separate and co-equal branch of government under Article III. While Congress established the lower federal courts, the Constitution created the Supreme Court, which sets its own rules. Congress has no constitutional power to tell the Justices how to run the Court.</p><p> The supposed justification for this radical remaking of the Court is a series of media articles that reveal little more than that Justices have rich friends. They have on occasion even flown on private jets, oh my. In the latest supposed scandal, the staff of Justice Sonia Sotomayor is reported to have encouraged the sale of her books coinciding with her appearances at universities. In none of these cases has anyone found a real conflict of interest involving the Justices and a case or ruling.</p><h4> ***</h4><p> The partisan nature of this exercise is clear from the one-sided efforts at fact-finding. Last week Messrs. Whitehouse and Durbin sent a letter to Leonard Leo, who advised President Trump on judicial nominations and is friends with some of the conservative Justices.</p><p> The letter requests “an itemized list of all gifts, payments, and items of value . 。 。 to any Justice of the Supreme Court or a member of the Justice&#39;s family which you had a role in facilitating or arranging.” We could find no evidence of similar curiosity about the liberal Justices and their friends.</p><p> Damaging the Court has been Mr. Whitehouse&#39;s explicit goal since progressives lost their majority and the Court as a second legislature. In 2019 he and four other Senate Democrats wrote a notorious amicus brief in a gun-rights case that said “the Supreme Court is not well.” The brief threatened, mob-style, that if the Court didn&#39;t “heal itself,” it might have to be “restructured.”</p><p> Democrats don&#39;t currently have the votes to break the Senate filibuster and pack the Court, but watch out when they do. Meantime, their ethics ruse is an attempt to intimidate and control the Justices by other means. It deserves to be called out as a betrayal of the Constitution that would destroy judicial independence. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B89B2690-0317-40F9-A22B-4C9D280DCCCC&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-supreme-court-control-act-whitehouse-durbin-recusal-ethics-1b2e9bd3&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Journal Editorial Report: The week&#39;s best and worst from Kim Strassel, Bill McGurn, Mary O&#39;Grady and Dan Henninger. Images: AP/EPA/Shutterstock/Reuters/Zuma Press Composite: Mark Kelly <span class="imageCredit">The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 20:13:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-supreme-court-control-act-whitehouse-durbin-recusal-ethics-1b2e9bd3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-supreme-court-control-act-whitehouse-durbin-recusal-ethics-1b2e9bd3<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category> ethics</category><category> panel</category><category> circuit court judges</category><category> complaints</category><category> integrity</category><category> recusal</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Ethical Issues</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Social Issues</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>ethical issues</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>social issues</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Supreme Court Control Act]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> New ethics proposals from Senate Democrats are a scheme to destroy the Court&#39;s independence. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590082170044941344"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590082170044941344"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">July 16, 2023 4:13 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-supreme-court-control-act-whitehouse-durbin-recusal-ethics-1b2e9bd3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818024?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Senator Sheldon Whitehouse (D-RI) speaking with Senator Dick Durbin (D-IL) at a hearing of the Senate Judiciary Committee on June 13.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Michael Brochstein/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The Supreme Court has finished its business for the summer, but Senate Democrats never finish trashing the Justices. The Judiciary Committee that scoured Brett Kavanaugh&#39;s high-school yearbook is preparing to pass new rules under the guise of ethics reform that are intended to put the Justices on a political leash.</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> The effort is led by Rhode Island Sen. Sheldon Whitehouse and his more senior political front man, Judiciary Chairman Dick Durbin. They&#39;re playing off recent media reports that claim ethics violations without showing any real violations. But that&#39;s enough of an excuse for claiming to want to protect the Court&#39;s reputation while actually destroying it.</p><h4> ***</h4><p> Their Supreme Court Ethics, Recusal, and Transparency Act would require the Court to establish a Code of Conduct within 180 days. It would also set disclosure rules for “gifts, income, and reimbursements required to be disclosed under the Standing Rules of the Senate and the Rules of the House of Representatives.”</p><p> Treating judges like Members of Congress is exactly the wrong model to follow. The nine Justices are appointees with lifetime tenure under the Constitution in order to insulate them from political pressure. Legislators are political actors accountable to voters for their relationships with campaign contributors and interest groups.</p><p> The Senate ethics scheme would drop the Justices into a new political maelstrom. The bill invites ethics complaints alleging that a Justice violates the new rules or “has otherwise engaged in conduct that undermines the integrity of the Supreme Court.” That open-ended standard is an invitation to groups on the left and right to file endless complaints against the Justices to create the appearance of wrongdoing or conflicts of interest.</p><p> The complaints would be handled by a five-member panel of chief judges from the circuit courts. That would further politicize the judiciary by asking lower-court judges to rule on the ethics of Justices who decide whether to hear appeals of their rulings. The judges would be under enormous pressure to act against Justices with a different judicial philosophy.</p><p> The bill also lays out “circumstances requiring disqualification” to hear a case—more commonly known as recusal. The Justices currently make their own decisions on recusal based on relatively narrow criteria such as whether they have a financial interest in a case. Political demands for recusal are becoming more common, but most can be ignored.</p><p> The Senate bill sets up a process for a three-judge panel of judges to review a “motion” by a party for recusal. Such motions would proliferate, as the parties and interests angle to eliminate a Justice they think might rule against them. The Democratic goal here is thinning the Court on a case by case basis to influence decisions. It&#39;s a different means than packing the Court by adding Justices, but the purpose is similar.</p><p> The Founders anticipated this political temptation, which is why they created the judiciary as a separate and co-equal branch of government under Article III. While Congress established the lower federal courts, the Constitution created the Supreme Court, which sets its own rules. Congress has no constitutional power to tell the Justices how to run the Court.</p><p> The supposed justification for this radical remaking of the Court is a series of media articles that reveal little more than that Justices have rich friends. They have on occasion even flown on private jets, oh my. In the latest supposed scandal, the staff of Justice Sonia Sotomayor is reported to have encouraged the sale of her books coinciding with her appearances at universities. In none of these cases has anyone found a real conflict of interest involving the Justices and a case or ruling.</p><h4> ***</h4><p> The partisan nature of this exercise is clear from the one-sided efforts at fact-finding. Last week Messrs. Whitehouse and Durbin sent a letter to Leonard Leo, who advised President Trump on judicial nominations and is friends with some of the conservative Justices.</p><p> The letter requests “an itemized list of all gifts, payments, and items of value . 。 。 to any Justice of the Supreme Court or a member of the Justice&#39;s family which you had a role in facilitating or arranging.” We could find no evidence of similar curiosity about the liberal Justices and their friends.</p><p> Damaging the Court has been Mr. Whitehouse&#39;s explicit goal since progressives lost their majority and the Court as a second legislature. In 2019 he and four other Senate Democrats wrote a notorious amicus brief in a gun-rights case that said “the Supreme Court is not well.” The brief threatened, mob-style, that if the Court didn&#39;t “heal itself,” it might have to be “restructured.”</p><p> Democrats don&#39;t currently have the votes to break the Senate filibuster and pack the Court, but watch out when they do. Meantime, their ethics ruse is an attempt to intimidate and control the Justices by other means. It deserves to be called out as a betrayal of the Constitution that would destroy judicial independence. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B89B2690-0317-40F9-A22B-4C9D280DCCCC&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-supreme-court-control-act-whitehouse-durbin-recusal-ethics-1b2e9bd3&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Journal Editorial Report: The week&#39;s best and worst from Kim Strassel, Bill McGurn, Mary O&#39;Grady and Dan Henninger. Images: AP/EPA/Shutterstock/Reuters/Zuma Press Composite: Mark Kelly <span class="imageCredit">The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 20:13:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-supreme-court-control-act-whitehouse-durbin-recusal-ethics-1b2e9bd3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-supreme-court-control-act-whitehouse-durbin-recusal-ethics-1b2e9bd3<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category> ethics</category><category> panel</category><category> circuit court judges</category><category> complaints</category><category> integrity</category><category> recusal</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Ethical Issues</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Social Issues</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>ethical issues</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>social issues</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[America’s Trade Abdication]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Britain joins the Indo-Pacific pact, as the US sits on the sidelines. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590092122573192784"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590092122573192784"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">July 16, 2023 4:12 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-trade-abdication-indo-pacific-pact-britain-tpp-c584633e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818067?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> US Trade Representative Katherine Tai in March.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: ADRIANO MACHADO/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The United Kingdom signed onto the Indo-Pacific trade pact on Sunday, becoming the first European country to join the 11-nation Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership (CPTPP). In addition to its economic benefits for Britain, the event is notable for exposing America&#39;s growing trade failures.</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> The CPTPP is the successor to the Trans-Pacific Partnership that <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">Donald Trump</a> walked away from in 2017. It includes Canada, Mexico, Japan, Australia, Vietnam, Singapore and Malaysia, among others. The pact excludes China, which made it an ideal opportunity to shape global trade rules and expand US economic influence in the fastest-growing part of the world. The parties moved on without the US, and now others want to get in on the action.</p><p> That doesn&#39;t include the US After criticizing Mr. Trump&#39;s trade policy as a candidate, President Biden has been nearly as protectionist in office. He&#39;s retained most Trump tariffs, and he&#39;s resisted new bilateral or other trade deals. He&#39;s even left Britain in the cold, despite its compatibility with the US economy and post-Brexit interest in a bilateral deal.</p><p> The Administration launched the Indo-Pacific Economic Framework (IPEF) last year, but it has since been exposed as vacuous. The US won&#39;t negotiate tariff reductions or market access measures. US companies say the White House even seems to be backtracking on its promise to promote new standards for digital trade.</p><p> Thirty-six business and agriculture groups expressed their dismay about the failures of IPEF in a May letter to Commerce Secretary Gina Raimondo and US Trade Representative Katherine Tai. “A &#39;work-centric&#39; trade agenda must reflect how American companies and the workers they employ suffer together when we are barred from selling the goods and services we produce in foreign markets,” they wrote.</p><p> The White House is by all accounts afraid of debating Mr. Trump on the benefits of trade. That leaves the US on the sidelines as the rest of the world negotiates new trade deals, including the European Union with Indonesia and India. This also leaves the US the odd economic man out in the Indo-Pacific even as US companies urgently need supply-chain alternatives to China. The costs of Mr. Biden&#39;s trade abdication are growing by the month. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=FA4C6CE6-5CE3-4E1A-B41B-3E1F97CDAEF6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Famericas-trade-abdication-indo-pacific-pact-britain-tpp-c584633e&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Journal Editorial Report: Christopher Wray won&#39;t talk about the FBI and conservatives.图片：美联社/祖玛出版社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 20:12:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-trade-abdication-indo-pacific-pact-britain-tpp-c584633e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-trade-abdication-indo-pacific-pact-britain-tpp-c584633e<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category> trade</category><category> indo-pacific pact</category><category> european union</category><category> britain</category><category> supply chain</category><category> tpp</category><category> china</category><category> Trade/External Payments</category><category> Physical Trade</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>唐纳德·特朗普</category><category>external payments</category><category> physical trade</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[More Dollars Follow Ohio Students]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The Buckeye State makes vouchers universal and boosts charter schools. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12705823021609713873204590081761327492600"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12705823021609713873204590081761327492600"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">July 16, 2023 4:11 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ohio-school-choice-vouchers-charter-schools-mike-dewine-383f5eb3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818021?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A bus drops students off at an elementary school in Dayton, Ohio</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: megan jelinger/Reuters</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Pennsylvania&#39;s Democratic Gov. Josh Shapiro sold students out by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/josh-shapiro-school-choice-vouchers-veto-matthew-bradford-kim-ward-joe-pittman-pennsylvania-6707d3b9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">backing down on a school voucher proposal</a> this month, but his Republican neighbor Gov. Mike DeWine is doing better in Ohio. The Governor and the GOP Legislature recently narrowed the funding gap between charter and district schools and opened a state voucher program to all families, making the Buckeye State the latest to offer universal school choice.</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Ohio&#39;s EdChoice Scholarship Program has offered K-12 school vouchers to families with income under 250% of the federal poverty level—about $75,000 for a family of four—or to families with students attending the state&#39;s worst-performing schools. The new law opens the vouchers to any family regardless of income or school attendance.</p><p> The full scholarship amount rises to $6,165 from about $5,500 for K-8 students, and to $8,407 from $7,500 for high school. The voucher tapers down for families making more than 450% of the poverty level. According to an analysis from Ohio&#39;s Legislative Service Commission, more than 90,000 students currently attend private school without a scholarship and now could be eligible.</p><p> The new law is also a step toward fairness for charter schools, a priority for Mr. DeWine. Charters will get a roughly 12% increase in state funding, plus $1,000 per student in facilities funding—twice as much as before. Charter schools that are considered high-performing according to state criteria—roughly a third of the state&#39;s charters—receive supplemental funding per student and now will see increases in those amounts.</p><p> Overall, high-performing charters should see a roughly 40% boost in funding, <a href="https://fordhaminstitute.org/ohio/commentary/ohio-lawmakers-pass-historic-policies-charter-schools-private-school-choice" target="_blank" class="icon none">according to</a> the Fordham Institute, putting them at about 90% of what district schools receive. The average brick-and-mortar Ohio charter school will receive roughly 85% of district-school funding, up from 70% currently.</p><p> More than 100,000 students attend Ohio&#39;s charter schools, which are especially important for the state&#39;s inner-city students. Out of 26 cities measured, Cleveland students posted the biggest drop in National Assessment of Educational Progress reading scores last year compared to 2019. Cleveland also has its own school voucher program, and one common-sense measure from the Legislature was to allow students to take the vouchers to any private school—not only schools within the district.</p><p> Ohio has expanded its school choice offerings from cities to suburbs over the years. Good for Gov. DeWine and the Legislature for making private schools available to more families, and let&#39;s hope they have their eye on education savings accounts next. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=25232CEE-3316-437F-9EED-9F82FA7070FC&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fohio-school-choice-vouchers-charter-schools-mike-dewine-383f5eb3&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Journal Editorial Report: But some in the GOP don&#39;t like the picks. Images: Getty Images/Zuma Press Composite: Mark Kelly <span class="imageCredit">The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 20:11:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ohio-school-choice-vouchers-charter-schools-mike-dewine-383f5eb3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ohio-school-choice-vouchers-charter-schools-mike-dewine-383f5eb3<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Regional Politics</category><category> School</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Mike DeWine</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>regional politics</category><category> school</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item></channel></rss>